title: For Sale:  Arsenal SAM7K AK AK47 layaway SAM7K-01
postcontent: I'm presenting an Arsenal SAM7K-01. The milled receiver is marked "Made in Bulgaria" and "Arsenal Las Vegas NV USA". It has the circle 10 brand if you're familiar with that. The milled receiver makes for a more solid firearm. I don't believe it necessarily makes it more reliable but there's definitely a nice solid feel to them. This pistol is chambered in 7.62X39. The tip up dust cover is hinged near the front trunnion. It opens and closes easily. The fire control parts feature a dual hook trigger. The trigger has no slack, 3/8" of fairly smooth creep, and a crisp let off at an estimated five pounds. This could be smoothed into a nice trigger pull. The safety selector can be engaged from the traditional lever on the right, but Arsenal incorporated a left side lever like on the Galil. That left side selector is forward on safe and must me moved rearward for fire. Not the most desirable but, when you examine the mechanism, you'll understand why it had to be that way. There is a receiver rail on the left side. The dust cover mounted rear flip sight has two settings: a notch and a ghost ring. You select which you wish to use via the lever on the right side. While the flip sight can easily be changed without the lever, the lever is probably welcome when wearing thick gloves. The front sight is standard AK adjustable for elevation by screwing the post in or out, and for windage by drifting the cylinder. The front sight and gas block assembly has a muzzle device attached. Here's how I think it's arranged...I believe the block is threaded, probably 24mm. The barrel extends about 2.5" beyond the threads. The device is threaded onto the gas block threads and pinned into place. Thus, the muzzle device is a mock whatever. It is neither a brake nor a flash hider. The pistol comes with a 5rd magazine. I have 30rd mags and mag kits

My dad used to shoot a lot of bowling pin shoots with this sight mounted on his 357 revolver. They've started doing steel shoots near him so he pulled his revolver out of the safe, only to find that the Tasco wasn't quite big enough for his eyes anymore. We went shooting last weekend and got him sighted in with a new red dot, and he gave me this one.

Here's the trouble - he took the battery (batteries?) out so they wouldn't corrode, and I can't figure out what is supposed to go in there. I called Tasco and they told me that all of their ProPoint sights take CR2032 lithium coin batteries - well, I'm no engineer but there isn't any way one of those will fit in there.

I tried all kinds of little batteries and the closest I could get was a pair of Energizer 76 batteries out of a Christmas ornament - it lit up very briefly and then went out again, I'm guessing because the batteries were weak? Maybe it takes lithium batteries instead? I don't know, but it's not doing anything for me at this point.  I'm thinking $40 OBO
